  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Zero Hunger - Zero Emissions:  Restricted Funding: R07466</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Oxfam will partner with the International Centre for Climate Change and Development (ICCCAD)  in Bangladesh on a project to democratise decision -making around &quot;zero -zero&quot;  - piloting methods to investigate how citizens can be involved and their voices heard in national debates on how to achieve zero hunger goals and concurrently move to zero net greenhouse gas emissions.   Zero -zero is the goal that we  - the nations of the world  - have to concurrently achieve zero net Greenhouse Gas (GHG) emissions and zero hunger  - both together within pretty much the same time frame  - and therefore how do we make that happen with maximum synergy and minimal trade -offs (a process which demands citizen participation).  The zero emissions goal is what agreed climate change targets necessitates, especially now that nations at Paris agreed to work to limit warming to 1.5 degrees C  - a more ambitious target than the already ambitious 2 degrees. Two degrees was held to be the likely level of &quot;dangerous&quot; climate change; observations of actual changes, and impacts, have since prompted this greater level of ambition. To get to 1.5 requires no net emissions ASAP (estimates vary but basically within the next decade (though some estimates say we have 12 months)). That requires, obviously, massive decarbonisation and consequent reorientation of societies globally....let&apos;s assume that even if there is much faster progress that won&apos;t happen so the other strategy increasingly being considered likely to be needed is to pull back the carbon &quot;overshoot&quot; via &quot;Negative Emissions Technologies&quot;  - sucking carbon out and somehow storing it. An example of such a Negative Emissions Technologies (NET) would be (BECCS), Bio -Energy with Carbon Capture + Storage  - basically plant crops, harvest and burn them for biofuel/heating/electricity to replace oil, gas, coal, and sequester the emissions. The snag is that that would require huge areas of (relatively fertile) land...  Which is a good example of the possible</narrative>
  </description>
